SIMPLE: help
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Help
<hw>Help</hw> <pr>(h⟦ecr⟧lp)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Helped</conjf> <pr>(h⟦ecr⟧lpt)</pr>
(<mark>Obs</mark>. <pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Holp</conjf>
<pr>(h⟦omac⟧lp)</pr>, <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Holpen</conjf>
<pr>(h⟦omac⟧l"p'n)</pr>); <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Helping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>helpan</ets>; akin to
OS. <ets>helpan</ets>, D. <ets>helpen</ets>, G. <ets>helfen</ets>, OHG.
<ets>helfan</ets>, Icel. <ets>hj⟦amac⟧lpa</ets>, Sw. <ets>hjelpa</ets>,
Dan. <ets>hielpe</ets>, Goth. <ets>hilpan</ets>; cf. Lith.
<ets>szelpti</ets>, and Skr. <ets>klp</ets> to be fitting.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To furnish with strength or means for the successful
performance of any action or the attainment of any object; to aid; to
assist; <as>as, to <ex>help</ex> a man in his work; to <ex>help</ex> one
to remember</as>; -- the following infinitive is commonly used without
<it>to</it>; <as>as, ⟦ldquo⟧<ex>Help</ex> me scale yon
balcony.⟦rdquo⟧</as></def> <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To furnish with the means of deliverance from
trouble; <as>as, to <ex>help</ex> one in distress; to <ex>help</ex> one
out of prison.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧God <xex>help</xex>, poor souls, how
idly do they talk!⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To furnish with relief, as in pain or disease; to be
of avail against; -- sometimes with <xex>of</xex> before a word
designating the pain or disease, and sometimes having such a word for
the direct object.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>help</xex> him of his
blindness.⟦rdquo⟧ <-- now, <it>in</it> is used for that function; -- "to
help him in his misery" --> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The true calamus <qex>helps</qex> coughs.</q>
<rj><qau>Gerarde.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 684 --></p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To change for the better; to remedy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cease to lament for what thou canst not <qex>help</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To prevent; to hinder; as, the evil approaches, and
who can <xex>help</xex> it?</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To forbear; to avoid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can not <qex>help</qex> remarking the resemblance betwixt him
and our author.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><-- often used with "but" -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To wait upon, as the guests at table, by carving and
passing food.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To help forward</b></col>, <cd>to assist in
advancing.</cd> -- <col><b>To help off</b></col>, <cd>to help to go or
pass away, as time; to assist in removing.</cd> <au>Locke.</au> --
<col><b>To help on</b></col>, <cd>to forward; to promote by aid.</cd> --
<col><b>To help out</b></col>, <cd>to aid, as in delivering from a
difficulty, or to aid in completing a design or task.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The god of learning and of light⟦br⟧
Would want a god himself <qex>to help</qex> him <qex>out</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To help over</b></col>, <cd>to enable to surmount; <as>as,
<ex>to help</ex> one <ex>over</ex> an obstacle</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To
help to</b></col>, <cd>to supply with; to furnish with; as, <xex>to
help</xex> one <xex>to</xex> soup.</cd> -- <col><b>To help up</b></col>,
<cd>to help (one) to get up; to assist in rising, as after a fall, and
the like.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧A man is well <xex>holp up</xex> that trusts to
you.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au></p></cs>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To aid; assist; succor; relieve; serve; support;
sustain; befriend.</syn> <usage> -- To <er>Help</er>, <er>Aid</er>,
<er>Assist</er>. These words all agree in the idea of affording relief
or support to a person under difficulties. <xex>Help</xex> turns
attention especially to the source of relief. If I fall into a pit, I
call for <xex>help</xex>; and he who <xex>helps</xex> me out does it by
an act of his own. <xex>Aid</xex> turns attention to the other side, and
supposes co⟦oum⟧peration on the part of him who is relieved; as, he
<xex>aided</xex> me in getting out of the pit; I got out by the
<xex>aid</xex> of a ladder which he brought. <xex>Assist</xex> has a
primary reference to relief afforded by a person who ⟦ldquo⟧stands
by⟦rdquo⟧ in order to relieve. It denotes both <xex>help</xex> and
<xex>aid</xex>. Thus, we say of a person who is weak, I
<xex>assisted</xex> him upstairs, or, he mounted the stairs by my
<xex>assistance</xex>. When <xex>help</xex> is used as a noun, it points
less distinctively and exclusively to the source of relief, or, in other
words, agrees more closely with <xex>aid</xex>. Thus we say, I got out
of a pit by the <xex>help</xex> of my friend.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Help</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Help
<hw>Help</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To lend aid or
assistance; to contribute strength or means; to avail or be of use; to
assist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A generous present <xex>helps</xex> to persuade, as well as an
agreeable person.</q> <rj><qau>Garth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To help out</b></col>, <cd>to lend aid; to bring a
supply.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Help</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Help
<hw>Help</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>help</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>hulp</ets>, G. <ets>h⟦uum⟧lfe</ets>, <ets>hilfe</ets>, Icel.
<ets>hj⟦amac⟧lp</ets>, Sw. <ets>hjelp</ets>, Dan. <ets>hielp</ets>. See
<er>Help</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Strength or means furnished toward promoting an
object, or deliverance from difficulty or distress; aid; ^; also, the
person or thing furnishing the aid; <as>as, he gave me a <ex>help</ex>
of fifty dollars</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Give us <qex>help</qex> from trouble, for vain is the
<qex>help</qex> of man.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lx. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God is . . . a very present <qex>help</qex> in trouble.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. xlvi. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Virtue is a friend and a <qex>help</qex> to nature.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Remedy; relief; <as>as, there is no <ex>help</ex>
for it</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A helper; one hired to help another; also, thew hole
force of hired helpers in any business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Specifically, a domestic servant, man or
woman.</def> <mark>[Local, U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Helper</ent>⟦br⟧
